  In this article, we will try to create a simple login feature using Next.js and Firebase Authentication. This article is intended for beginners who are new to Next.js as a framework for work or those who want to start building a web app based on the React framework and understand the general structure and workflow of Next.js.
  
  Basically, [**Next.js**](https://nextjs.org/docs) is a React framework based on SSR (Server‑Side Rendering). Unlike React.js, which uses CSR (Client‑Side Rendering), Next.js works like most full‑stack frameworks (such as Laravel, Spring Boot, etc.) that adopt an **opinionated framework** approach.
  
  **Prerequisite**
  
  - Understanding of basic web concepts (HTML, CSS, and JavaScript)
  - Understanding of [React](https://react.dev/learn) structure and its components
  - Node.js version 20+ (If your computer does not have it installed yet, please download and install Node.js from the following link: [https://nodejs.org/en/download](https://nodejs.org/en/download))
  - A code editor ( [Visual Studio Code](https://code.visualstudio.com/))
  - An active Gmail account (for logging into Firebase Console)
  
  **In this article, you will learn about:**
  
  - How to set up a project using Next.js version 16.
  - How to create UI components in Next.js.
  - How to integrate Firebase Authentication into our web app.
  - How to build a login feature using Firebase Authentication.
  
