  - After the installation is complete, you will see that several folders and files have been automatically created inside your project folder.
  
  ![](https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:311/1*sp0fOTk4QLReFtTrx3bLsg.png)
  
  Don’t worry. For now, we will learn the structure of the folders and files inside our Next.js project. Below are the functions of several folders and files that typically appear in a Next.js project structure:
  
  `.next/` **folder**
  
  - This folder is the build output (auto‑generated by Next.js). It is used to store compiled results, cache, server build artifacts, output bundling, and optimized static files.
  - You should not edit or commit this folder to Git.
  - Typically, when you run **npm run build** or **npm run dev**, this folder will be updated or regenerated automatically.
  
  `app/` **folder**
  
  - This folder is the core of the App Router and the main component of the application. All routing, layouts, server components, client components, and nested routes are defined here.
  - Inside the `app/` folder, there is a file called `layout.tsx`, which serves as the root layout or base structure of the application. The `layout.tsx` file functions as the main template and wraps all pages.
  
  `page.tsx` **file (inside the**`app/` **folder)**
  
  - This file is the default page for the `/` route. When the website is first opened, the default route of the application is `/`.
  - Every folder inside `app/` that contains a `page.tsx` file automatically becomes 1 route. Examples:
  
  ```
  app/page.tsx        → /
  app/about/page.tsx  → /about
  app/login/page.tsx  → /login
  ```
  
  `globals.css` **file (inside the**`app/` **folder)**
  
  - This is the global CSS file, used for global styling, CSS reset, Tailwind base layers, and custom global styles.
  - The file is usually imported inside `layout.tsx`:
  
  ```
  import './globals.css'
  ```
  
  `favicon.ico` **file (inside the**`app/` **folder)**
  
  - This is the browser tab icon (the icon displayed on the browser tab).
  - You can replace this file with another format such as SVG or PNG.
  
  `public/` **folder**
  
  - This folder contains static assets.
  - Files inside this folder are served directly without processing (e.g., images, fonts, PDFs, static JSON files, etc.).
  
  `.gitignore` **file**
  
  - This file specifies which files or folders should not be tracked by Git (hidden or excluded from your GitHub repository).
  
  `eslint.config.mjs` **file**
  
  - This file contains ESLint configuration.
  - It is used to define linting rules, coding standards, and static error detection. By default, Next.js includes the preset `next/core-web-vitals`.
  
  `next-env.d.ts` **file**
  
  - This is an auto‑generated TypeScript file.
  - You should not edit it manually, as it contains type definitions required by Next.js.
  
  `next.config.ts` **file**
  
  - This is the main configuration file for Next.js.
  - It is used for custom webpack configuration, environment variables, Image optimization domains, redirects & rewrites, output modes (standalone, edge, etc.), and experimental features.
  - This file is very important and can be edited according to your app’s needs by following the official Next.js documentation: [https://nextjs.org/docs/pages/api-reference/config/typescript](https://nextjs.org/docs/pages/api-reference/config/typescript)
  
  `tsconfig.json` **file**
  
  - This file contains TypeScript configuration.
  - It is used for path alias, strict mode, ES version targeting, and module resolution.
  
